    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-09-06T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-09-06T21:00:00-05:00" n="565"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d565">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/9965: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-09-07T10:00:00+08:00"
                            >September 7, 1937—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 6—4:39 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>619. My 574 [August 31, 6 p.m.]. Reply of Minister for Foreign Affairs has now
                    been received to the effect that river was closed because of absolute necessity
                    of the situation, that alleged report regrets any future hardships thus
                    resulting to shipping and nationals of friendly countries. British Embassy
                    informs me that it appealed to Generalissimo to make it possible for British
                    cruiser to leave river but that reply was in the negative. There seemed to me to
                    be nothing more that we can do at this end in this matter.</p>
                <p>Sent to the Department, Peiping, Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
